### Describe the bug

When a typed HTTP client is added to the container with `services.AddHttpClient<Type>()` if an `ILogger` is injected into `Type`'s constructor log messages written to the injected logger are not written to the console.


### Steps to reproduce

Steps to reproduce the behavior:

1. Using ASP.NET Core 2.2.6
2. Run this code

```csharp
services.AddHttpClient<TestApiService>();
```

```csharp
public class TestApiService
{
    private readonly ILogger _logger;
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public TestApiService(ILogger<TestApiService> logger, HttpClient httpClient)
    {
        _logger = logger;

        httpClient.BaseAddress = new Uri("http://localhost:5000");

        _httpClient = httpClient;
    }

    public async Task<HttpResponseMessage> GetStatus()
    {
        _logger.LogInformation("Calling /api/v1/status.");

        return await _httpClient.GetAsync("/api/v1/status");
    }
}
```
```csharp
[Route("api/v1")]
[ApiController]
public class ApiController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly TestApiService _testApiService;

    public ApiController(TestApiService testApiService)
    {
        _testApiService = testApiService;
    }

    [HttpGet("check")]
    public async void CheckLogging()
    {
        await _testApiService.GetStatus();
    }

    [HttpGet("status")]
    public string GetStatus()
    {
        return "Ok";
    }
}
```

3. GET http://localhost:5000/api/v1/check
4. Look at the console output


### Expected behavior

Informational log messages should be written to the console from `TestApiService`.


