## Problem
Page's very often want to set the title (from the browser's POV) and today that's typically done in Razor Pages by passing the desired title via the `ViewData` dictionary to the layout page and having it emit it in the HTML's `<title>` element:

``` html
@page
@model MyPageModel

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "My Page";
}

<h1>ViewData["Title"]</h1>
```

This isn't great for a few reasons, including it not being type safe (string names) and the page itself often wanting to access the title itself to show in an `<h1>` or similar, meaning it not only sets it in the `ViewData` but also reads it out again (which isn't as fast as just a literal or member access, and is another chance to mess up the string key name).

## Proposal
We could add a string property `PageTitle` to the built-in `PageModel` base class that makes it easy to set the page title from a page's model or from the cshtml in a code block, and have that property automatically set the value in the `ViewData["Title"]` location so that the only place in the app that has to read that now is layout page itself.

An app could do this with a custom page model base with a property like the following, but it would seem like a great general addition for everything to have:
``` c#
[ViewData]
public string Title { get; set; }
```

